analysis_racingtime

Author

Christian Magelssen

This quarto file analyzes the racing times. Every analysis, including models and plots, reported in the paper related to racing times can be found here. We start by loading the necessary packages and a custom function for data analysis.

options(scipen = 999)

Acquisition

Select data

The acquisition phase of the experiment covers Block 1 (forced exploration), and Block 2 and Block 3 (free-choice). Therefore, we filter those.

d_acquisition <- filter(d, session == "block1" | session == "block2" | session == "block3")

Coding contrasts

The next step is to set up the treatment contrasts. Instead of using the Intercept as the reference level, we code the Intercept to represent the Grand Mean. This coding scheme is known as simple coding (https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/library/r-library-contrast-coding-systems-for-categorical-variables/).â

# Simple code treatment
d_acquisition <- mutate(d_acquisition, treatment=as.factor(treatment)) # Turn it into factor
treatmentcoding <- contr.treatment(3) 
matrix <- matrix(rep(1/3, 6), ncol=2)
treatment_simplecoded <- treatmentcoding - matrix
contrasts(d_acquisition$treatment) <- treatment_simplecoded

# Simple code session
d_acquisition <- mutate(d_acquisition, session=as.factor(session))
treatmentcoding <- contr.treatment(3) 
matrix <- matrix(rep(1/3, 6), ncol=2)
session_simplecoded <- treatmentcoding - matrix
contrasts(d_acquisition$session) <- session_simplecoded

Models

# This model was singular
model_racingtime_acquisition_1 <- lmer(racingtime ~ session * treatment + (1 + session | skigroup/skier), REML=FALSE, data=d_acquisition)
# This model converged and was not singular
model_racingtime_acquisition_2 <- lmer(racingtime ~ session * treatment + (1 | skigroup) + (1 + session | skigroup:skier), REML=FALSE, data=d_acquisition)

We create latex files of these statistics with the following custom function

emm_model_racingtime_acquisition_2_tibble_block1 <- filter(emm_model_racingtime_acquisition_2_tibble, session == "block1")


write_emmeans_lmer <- function(model_output, model_name) {
  model_name <- as.character(model_name)
  
  # Create the folder if it doesn't exist
  folder_path <- "../../latex/statistics/marginalmeans"
  if (!dir.exists(folder_path)) {
    dir.create(folder_path)
  }
  
  # Loop over every row in d_emmean
  for (i in 1:nrow(model_output)) {
    row <- model_output[i, ]
    
    term <- as.character(row$treatment)
    session <- as.character(row$session)
    
    beta <- round(row$emmean, digits = 2)
    
    filename <- file.path(folder_path, paste("emmean_", model_name, "_", term, "_", session,".tex"))
    filename <- gsub(" ", "", filename, fixed = TRUE)
    cat(as.character(beta), file = filename)
  }
}

write_emmeans_lmer(emm_model_racingtime_acquisition_2_tibble_block1, "racingtimes_acquisition")

We write these estimates to latex code with the following custom function

write_beta_lmer <- function(model_output, model_name) {
  model_name <- as.character(model_name)
  
  # Create the folder if it doesn't exist
  folder_path <- "../../latex/statistics/beta"
  if (!dir.exists(folder_path)) {
    dir.create(folder_path)
  }
  
  # Loop over every row in d_emmean
  for (i in 1:nrow(model_output)) {
    row <- model_output[i, ]
    
    term <- as.character(row$term)
    
    beta <- round(row$estimate, digits = 2)
    
    filename <- file.path(folder_path, paste("beta_", model_name, "_", term, ".tex"))
    filename <- gsub(" ", "", filename, fixed = TRUE)
    cat(as.character(beta), file = filename)
  }
}
write_beta_lmer(model_racingtime_acquisition_estimates, "racingtimes_acquisition")

We write the test statistics to latex code with the following function

write_contrast_lmer <- function(model_output, model_name) {
  model_name <- as.character(model_name)
  
  # Create the folder if it doesn't exist
  folder_path <- "../../latex/statistics/contrasts"
  if (!dir.exists(folder_path)) {
    dir.create(folder_path)
  }
  
  p_value_writer <- function(p_value) {
    symbol <- ifelse(p_value > 0.001, " = ", " < ")
    p_value_format <- ifelse(p_value > 0.001, formatC(round(p_value, digits = 3), digits = 3, format = "f"), "0.001")
    write_p_value <- paste(symbol, p_value_format)
    return(write_p_value)
  }
  
  # Loop over every row in d_emmean
  for (i in 1:nrow(model_output)) {
    row <- model_output[i, ]
    
    term <- as.character(row$term)
    
    beta <- round(row$estimate, digits = 2)
    statistic <- round(row$statistic, digits = 2)
    df <- round(row$df, digits = 3)
    ci_low <- round(row$conf.low, digits = 2)
    ci_high <- round(row$conf.high, digits = 2)
    p_value <- row$p.value
    
    report <- paste("$\\beta$ =", beta,", 95\\% CI [",ci_low,", ", ci_high,"], $t$(", df, ") =", statistic,", $p$",p_value_writer(p_value))
    
    filename <- file.path(folder_path, paste("contrast_", model_name, "_", term, ".tex"))
    filename <- gsub(" ", "", filename, fixed = TRUE)
    cat(report, file = filename)
  }
}
write_contrast_lmer(model_racingtime_acquisition_combined, "racingtimes_acquisition")

Coding contrasts

The next step is to set up the treatment contrasts. Instead of using the Intercept as the reference level, we code the Intercept to represent the Grand Mean. This coding scheme is known as simple coding (https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/library/r-library-contrast-coding-systems-for-categorical-variables/).â

# Contrast session (two levels)
d_retention_and_transfer$session <- as.factor(d_retention_and_transfer$session)
treatmentcoding <- contr.treatment(2)
matrix <- matrix(rep(1/2, 2), ncol=1)
treatment_simplecoded <- treatmentcoding - matrix
contrasts(d_retention_and_transfer$session) <- treatment_simplecoded

# Contrast treatment (three levels)
d_retention_and_transfer$treatment <- as.factor(d_retention_and_transfer$treatment)
treatmentcoding <- contr.treatment(3)
matrix <- matrix(rep(1/3, 6), ncol=2)
treatment_simplecoded <- treatmentcoding - matrix
contrasts(d_retention_and_transfer$treatment) <- treatment_simplecoded
